messages.content: Hey Emi! I just got back from that photography workshop in the mountains. It was absolutely incredible! We spent three days shooting landscapes at sunrise and sunset. The light was magical.

messages.content: I brought my Sony A7R IV with a 24-70mm and a 70-200mm. The instructor taught us about long exposure for waterfalls and star trails. We did a 4-hour night shoot on the second day - my hands were freezing but the Milky Way shots came out stunning!

messages.content: Wow Milky Way photography! That's on my bucket list. Did you need a star tracker or was it just short exposures? I've heard the rule of 500 for avoiding star trails.
messages.rawContent: Wow Milky Way photography! That's on my bucket list. Did you need a star tracker or was it just short exposures? I've heard the rule of 500 for avoiding star trails.
messages.parsedContent: Wow Milky Way photography! That's on my bucket list. Did you need a star tracker or was it just short exposures? I've heard the rule of 500 for avoiding star trails.

messages.content: Exactly! We used the 500 rule - 500 divided by focal length gives you max shutter speed in seconds. For my 24mm that was about 20 seconds. No tracker needed for single shots. But for the intentional star trail photos we did 30-minute exposures with the tracker. The results were mind-blowing!

messages.content: It was in Colorado - Rocky Mountain National Park area. The workshop was $800 for three days including accommodation at a lodge. The instructor is this guy named David Chen, he's incredible. He has another one in Utah in April for desert landscapes and slot canyons. You should check out his website!
